@node "INSTALL" "INSTALLATION"
@next "USAGE"
@prev "DISCLAIMER"

@{b}INSTALLATION@{ub}


  If you are novice use the Install script included in this package. It will
  lead the install progress and you just confirm and correct its path.

  You can also install it manually. Just drop the QMaster executable and icon
  in some drawer you like. Then use the SetEnv comand as this (from CLI/Shell):

   1> setenv "QMASTER" "<the dirpath you choosed w/ trailing slash or column>"
   1> copy env:QMASTER envarc:

  Then copy the 'LoadQM' program to C: or another global comand path and that's
  it. You can also copy the arexx scripts to REXX: (Sys:rexx/) or someplace
  else.

  It is important to set the QMASTER env variable cause else the LoadQM program
  will not work.

  NOTE: The installer script doesn't currently check if the QMaster is
        previously installed.


                @{i}@{fg fill}Copyright © 1999 by Kenneth "Kenny" Nilsen@{ui}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "USAGE" "PROGRAM USAGE"
@next "AREXX"
@prev "INSTALL"

@{b}USAGE@{ub}


        The program can be started from either shell (CLI) or Workbench. From
        shell you can use the following syntax:

           QMASTER [-q]

        This will make QMaster resident. From shell you probably want to use
        the 'run' comand in front.

        If you use the '-q' option (from shell only) it will quit QMaster if it's
        running and then exit. It will still exit if QMaster wasn't running.

        Note that all arexx scripts bundled in this archive can start QMaster
        themselves after QMaster is installed correctly. This is due to the
        'LoadQM' executable.

        To stop QMaster from Workbench simply run it one more time (works from
        shell too). You will then get an about requester where you can select
        Quit or OK (OK will cancel the quit and allow QMaster to continue).

        You can also use the arexx comand @{"QUIT" link "QUIT" 0} to exit QMaster.


        Note that QMaster is not a commodity.


                @{i}@{fg fill}Copyright © 1999 by Kenneth "Kenny" Nilsen@{ui}@{fg text}

@endnode

