@node "HINTS" "HINTS"
@next "ADDENTRY"
@prev "AREXX"

@{b}HINTS@{ub}


        On this page you will find useful tips to avoid errors in your arexx
        programs:


        @{b}WRITING AREXXPROGRAMS@{ub}

        To be sure your arexx scripts will work then first install QMaster with
        the installer program. The installer will create a global env-var which
        will set the proper path to where QMaster is installed. Second: Use the
        LoadQM program in your scripts. The LoadQM comand should be placed in a
        directory which is in the global comand search path (such as C:). From
        your script you could use a simple first program line like,

                address command "LoadQM";if (rc~=0) then exit

        to start QMaster if it's not already running. The LoadQM will type the
        error message itself if the global path isn't set.


        @{b}FILENAMES@{ub}

        Always use double quotes around filenames. The Arexx interpreter
        removes the first pair of quotes when giving the comand to the arexx
        host. If your files then contains spaces they will be tokenized as two
        or more different args:

                MyComand "My File"

        will be given as:

                MYCOMAND My File

        to the host. If you use:

                MyComand "'My File'"  or  MyComand '"My File"'

        it will be given as:

                MYCOMAND 'My File'    or  MYCOMAND "My File"

        which will be interpretated correctly by the host (which removes the
        second pair of quotes).

        QMaster can handle any case in the comand names. Read your Arexx
        manual for more information.


        @{b}NUMBERS - FLOATS@{ub}

        The QMaster fraction resolution is calibrated for a maximum of four
        digits (1/10000th resolution). This is due to Studio 16's own internal
        resolution. Examples:

          Num=1.1234
          Num=1.123
          Num=1.1
          Num=1.
          Num=1
          Num=.1234

        You may use as many numbers as you like in the fraction, but the number
        will be cropped/truncated to four digits at max.

        You can give a float number to a comand that needs an integer number.
        The fraction will simply be ignored, but this behaviour is
        discourraged.

        You can actually give numbers in the form "$xxxx" and "%bbbbb" as these
        will be handled internally by QMaster. Remember that the fraction need
        to be in the same format.

          Num=$C.1B     => Num = 12.27 for QMaster
          Num=%10000.11 => Num = 16.3  for QMaster

        This only applies to QMaster and is not a normal Arexx feature. Note
        that you can not do mathematically operations on the numbers in these
        forms as they will be assumed to be alpha strings to arexx itself.


        @{b}STEMS@{ub}

        Make sure you don't use a variable that is defined by a stem. For
        example:

         STARTPOS="20.123" will make f.ex. SetEntry and AddEntry fail since:

         ENTRY.STARTPOS  will be "ENTRY.20.123" and not "ENTRY.STARTPOS"

        You can of course solve this by setting the stem in quotes like:

         "ENTRY.STARTPOS" = 12.3456

        To remove all stem settings you can use the Arexx built-in comand
        DROP:

          Drop ENTRY.

        Will remove ENTRY.* from the ARexx's symbol table (it will not remove
        STARTPOS in this example though).

        Also make sure that all stems are in uppercase. A thumbrule is to not
        use quotes around stem symbols as they then will always be converted to
        uppercase.


        @{b}RESOURCE TRACKING@{ub}

        QMaster provide a powerful resource tracking environment. This RTE will
        check pointers (Cue files and progress bars) if they are valid and if
        your script quits without cleaning up you can simply issue a
        "@{"RESOURCETRACK" link "RESOURCETRACK" 0}" comand to the host or simply quit QMaster which activate
        the RTE check. Resources that are found left in memory will be removed.
        The RTE will make sure the other comands fails instead of crash if the
        ID you give is invalid.

        Never issue a ResourceTrack while a script is executing.


        @{b}DOCUMENTATION@{ub}

        Result in the document referes always to the RESULT variable reserved
        by ARexx. To get a RESULT you must set "OPTIONS RESULTS" in your
        scripts. This is very important to do cause else you will miss the ID
        of f.ex. OpenCue which will then leave resources in memory and make
        other functions fail.

        The "special ID" or ID or File ID is returned by the OpenCue and
        CreateCue comands. All comand (except a few) needs this ID to work.
        You should not alter or manipulate this value.

        On each comand description page you will find a button at the bottom
        called "Comand list". This button will brin you to the comand list.


        @{b}ERRORS@{ub}

        @{b}ALWAYS@{ub} check comands for errors. Every comand is capable of
        returning atleast WARN (RC=5) or higher which means there was an error.
        You can set up an error interrupt (on signal error - see arexx manual
        for more information) to trap errors and handle them.

        RC is a reserved variable by ARexx. If RC=0 then the comand was
        successful.

        If RC=5 (WARN) an error occured, not @{i}necessarly@{ui} your fault
        (user aborted a requester, disk full etc.).

        If RC=10 (ERROR) then there was a syntax error or a number was out of
        range, for example track number was less than 1 or greater that 100. A
        script should not return 10 in any case. If so you need to debug it before
        releasing it.

        If RC=20 (FATAL) then the command was typed wrong or you didn't address
        QMaster. Never publish a script returning warnings 10 or 20.

        QMASTER has reserved a symbol named "QMASTER.LASTERROR". This symbol is
        read-only. The symbol will show what actually went wrong if a comand
        failed (if possible). Eg. if OpenCue failed you can find out if
        it's due to the file didn't exist or you was out of memory etc.


        @{b}LIMITATIONS@{ub}

        QMASTER operates with a limit of 100 tracks and each track can contain
        maximum 5000 entries (4 tracks and 15 entries in demo version). If of
        some strange reason this isn't enough contact @{"me" LINK "CREDITS" 0} and I will increase the
        limits on entries (Studio 16 can't handle more than 100 tracks anyway).

        You can only access functions using STEMs from arexx scripts ! This is
        due to the behaviour of the RVI interface (refer to "Commodore's
        Programmer's guide to Arexx®"). This mean you cannot call comands from
        your own applications if they need stems. Also the QMASTER.LASTERROR
        cannot be read if so.


        @{b}GENERAL@{ub}

        If includefile or studio16file.i|h is refered in a section it referes
        to the developer documentation available in the
        dev/misc/Studio16add.lha archive from AmiNet. This archive is freeware.

        For more information you can join the Studio 16 mailing list by sending
        an email to majordomo@thule.no and type:
        "subscribe studio16 <your email>" on one line in body text. No subject
        needed.


@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}


                @{i}@{fg fill}Copyright © 1999 by Kenneth "Kenny" Nilsen@{ui}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "ADDENTRY" "ADDENTRY <id> <track> <stem>"
@next "ADDTRACK"
@prev "HINTS"

Name
        ADDENTRY <id> <track> <stem>

Function

        Adds an entry to a track. The entry can be an audio or arexx entry. By
        using a stem you can set many different settings at once. The entry
        will be sorted at once based on the <stem>.STARTPOS. If an already
        existing entry has the same <stem>.STARTPOS time this comand will fail.
        You will be responsible to keep track of the entries you add.

        For AUDIO stems you should set <stem>.CROPOUT or else the entry will
        show as a small stripe in the Cuelist editor.

        The entry must be of the same type as the track you're adding to.
        Default is AUDIO type.

        If <stem>.STARTPOS is equal to an existing one the comand will fail
        (overlap).

Synopsis

        <special ID> <number> <string>

Inputs

        <id>    = file ID (see @{"OpenCue" link "OPENCUE" 0})
        <track> = add entry to this track. Note that entry type must be the
                  same as track type. Range 1-100
        <stem>  = different settings

        Common stems:

        <stem>.ENTRYTYPE        String type. Can be "AUDIO" or "AREXX"
        <stem>.NAME             String path/name on entry. Def. to no name.
        <stem>.STATUS           See include file "studio16file.i|h". Def. 2
        <stem>.STARTPOS         Start number of seconds (float). Def. 0
        <stem>.GROUPID          If not null all entries with this number will
                                be grouped. Different groups can be made. Def.0
                                Try to keep value in range 0-255.

        Stems for Audio entry (sample):

        <stem>.ENDPOS           End number of seconds (float). Def. 0
        <stem>.FADEINTYPE       See include file "studio16file.i|h". Def. 0
        <stem>.FADEOUTTYPE      See include file "studio16file.i|h". Def. 0
        <stem>.FADEINTIME       Number of seconds a fade will last (float)
        <stem>.FADEOUTTIME      Number of seconds a fade will last (float)
        <stem>.CROPIN           Number of samples to skip at start. Def. to 0
        <stem>.CROPOUT          Length in number of samples. Def. to 0
        <stem>.VOLUME           Volume for this entry. Def 100*32 (see include)
        <stem>.PAN              Pan on this entry. Def. 100*32 (see include)

        Stems for Arexx entry (event):

        <stem>.SMPTE            SMPTE stamp in format "HH:MM:SS:FF"
        <stem>.CMD1             Strings for cmd1-9.
        <stem>.CMD2
        <stem>.CMD3
        <stem>.CMD4
        <stem>.CMD5
        <stem>.CMD6
        <stem>.CMD7
        <stem>.CMD8
        <stem>.CMD9

        The <stem>.STARTPOS is required as well as <stem>.ENDPOS (for AUDIO
        type). Defaults to AUDIO type if no <stem>.TRACKTYPE is specified.

Results
        Entrynumber

Errors
        If RC=10 then there the track number was out of range.

        If RC=5 then there where probably an overlap, error in a stem or not
        enough memory.

Note
        You should not assume an entry's position since if an entry is inserted
        on a track the entries after will move one position.

Example
	GetSamplePrefs "'"MySample"'" SAMP
        if (rc~=0) then do
                say QMASTER.LASTERROR;exit 5;end

        ENTRY.NAME="'"MySample"'"
	ENTRY.CROPOUT=SAMP.SIZE

        AddEntry MyID 1 ENTRY
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say result

See also
        @{"RemEntry" link "REMENTRY" 0}
        @{"SetEntry" link "SETENTRY" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "ADDTRACK" "ADDTRACK <id> <stem>"
@next "CARDS"
@prev "ADDENTRY"

Name
        ADDTRACK <id> [stem]

Function
        Adds an empty track to a Cuelist file. The track can be of AUDIO or
        AREXX type.

Synopsis
        <special ID> [<string>]

Inputs
        <id>    = file ID (see OpenCuelistfile)
        [stem]  = optional stem containing different settings:

        Common stems:

        <stem>.TRACKTYPE        String for AUDIO or AREXX type. Def. AUDIO
        <stem>.TRACKNAME        String name on track. Def. to "Audio" or "AREXX"
        <stem>.TRACKPREFS       See studio16file.i|h include

        Stems for Audio tracks:

        <stem>.PLAYCHANNEL      String name on play channel. See note below.
        <stem>.RECORDCHANNEL    String name on record channel. See note below.
        <stem>.SAMPLERATE       Sample rate to use on track. Def. 44100
        <stem>.UNSELECTEDPREFS  See studio16file.i|h include
        <stem>.SELECTEDPREFS    See studio16file.i|h include

        Stem for Arexx track:

        <stem>.PORTNAME         Stringname on port to use on events


        If no stems are specified the track will default to AUDIO type.

Results
        Result is the new track number if success (can also be used as number
        of tracks in cuelist file).

Errors
        If 5 the tracktable was probably full or out of memory. Settings may be
        wrong.

Note
        The play and record channels can be different names based on how many
        cards you have installed. Defaults to "Any" (string) for play channel
        and record channel. However, consider the following:

        For single card users you can specify the channels like this:
        "AD516.Play 1" will use AD516 play channel 1.

        For record channels you must use this methode:
        "AD516.Input L" will use left input.

        For multicard users you can use a card like this:
        "AD516_#1.Play 2" will use card 1 channel 2

        For record channels you must use this methode:
        "AD516_#2.Output R" will use card 2's right output.

        Studio 16's Cuelist editor will handle singlecard files on multicards
        system and vica verca automatically.

Example
        TRACK.TRACKTYPE="AREXX"
        TRACK.TRACKNAME="RX Chan"
        TRACK.PREFS=1   /* selected */
        TRACK.PORTNAME="REXX"

        AddTrack MyID TRACK
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say result

See also
        @{"RemTrack" link "REMTRACK" 0}
        @{"SetTrack" link "SETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "CARDS" "CARDS <stem>"
@next "CLOSECUE"
@prev "ADDTRACK"

Name
        CARDS <stem>

Function
        This comand is used to obtain hardware info about Sunrize cards
        installed. It will set stems with numbers of cards and cards in use.

Synopsis
        <string>

Inputs
        stem    = stem to put the data in

        The stem is expanded to:

        <stem>.AD516    - number of AD516 cards installed
        <stem>.AD1012   - number of AD1012 cards installed
        <stem>.INUSE    - number of cards in use

Results
        none

Errors
        if RC=5 then the stems couldn't be set.

Note
        The stems are read-only.

Example

        Cards HARDWARE
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

        say "AD516 cards : "HARDWARE.AD516
        say "AD1012 cards: "HARDWARE.AD1012
        say "Cards in use: "HARDWARE.INUSE


See also
        @{"Video" link "VIDEO" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "CLOSECUE" "CLOSECUE <id>"
@next "CLOSEPROGRESS"
@prev "CARDS"

Name
        CLOSECUE <id>

Function
        Closes an already opened Cuelist file. The comand will not save data -
        only free memory used by the OpenCue comand. This comand should be
        used everytime you are done with a Cuelist file and/or exits (see
        note). To save altered data use the @{"UPDATECUE" link "UPDATECUE" 0} comand.

Synopsis
        <special ID>

Inputs
        <id>    = file ID

Results
        none

<Errors
        if RC=5 then the ID was wrong

Note

Example

        CloseCue MyID
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "OK"

See also
        @{"OpenCue" link "OPENCUE" 0}
        @{"UpdateCue" link "UPDATECUE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "CLOSEPROGRESS" "CLOSEPROGRESS <progress>"
@next "COPYTRACK"
@prev "CLOSECUE"

Name
        CLOSEPROGRESS <progress>

Function
        Closes a progress bar window opened with @{"INITPROGRESS" link "INITPROGRESS" 0}. It cleans up
        memory and resources.

Synopsis
        <special ID>

Inputs
        progress = progress ID returned by InitProgress

Results
        none

Errors
        RC=5 if invalid ID

Note

Example
        CloseProgress p
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

See also
        @{"INITPROGRESS" link "INITPROGRESS" 0}
        @{"UPDATEPROGRESS" link "UPDATEPROGRESS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "COPYTRACK" "COPYTRACK <id> <track>"
@next "CREATECUE"
@prev "CLOSEPROGRESS"

Name
        COPYTRACK <id> <track>

Function
        Copies a track into a copy buffer. The track copied can be pasted to
        any other Cuelist files (IDs). All entries and settings are copied as
        well and is kept until QMaster quits or you copy another track which
        then will free the old date (if any) and allocate space for the new
        data.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        <id>    = file ID
        <track> = track (1-100) you want to make a copy of

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then the track probably didn't exists or you was out of memory.

Note
        When pasting it to another cuelist file ID you should check that the
        preferences keep a TOTALLENGTH long enough to contain every entries
        that may be defined. Check the last entry to see if it passes the
        totoallength in your cuelist file.

Example
        CopyTrack MyID 1
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "OK"

See also
        @{"PasteTrack" link "PASTETRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "CREATECUE" "CREATECUE <filename> <stem>"
@next "CUTTRACK"
@prev "COPYTRACK"

Name
        CREATECUE <filename> [stem]

Function
        Creates a new cuelist file header on disk. The new cuelist file only
        contains a preference header. This cuelist file will then be loaded
        into memory and threated as if it was opened with OpenCue. You need to
        close the ID with CloseCue.

        Use this command to create a new Cuelist file from scratch.

Synopsis
        <string> [<string>]

Inputs
        filename      = path and filename.
        stem          = Optional preference settings. You don't need to give
                        the stem name as arg.

        See @{"SetPrefs" link "SETPREFS" 0} for details on the stems.

Results
        A file ID (as with OpenCue)

Errors
        If RC=5 then the comand could probably not create the new file or the
        prefs contained an error or you was out of memory or diskspace.

Note

Example
        Drop PREFS.
        PREFS.CUELISTNAME="Test.Cue"
        PREFS.TOTALLENGTH=5*60*100  /* 5 minuttes */
        CreateCue "'Studio16_3:Cuelists/Test.Cue'" PREFS
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "OK"

See also
        @{"OpenCue" link "OPENCUE" 0}
        @{"CloseCue" link "CLOSECUE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "CUTTRACK" "CUTTRACK <id> <track>"
@next "GETCUERATE"
@prev "CREATECUE"

Name
        CUTTRACK <id> <track>

Function
        Same function as RemTrack, but the cut track is stored at the internal
        clip and can be pasted with PasteTrack.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        file ID = ID from OpenCue
        track   = track (1-100) to cut.

Results
        Number of tracks left in RESULT.

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number was out of track
        If RC=5 then track didn't exist or out of memory

Note
        Note that a track previously stored at clip will be cleared.

Example
        CutTrack MyID 2
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

See also
        @{"RemTrack" link "REMTRACK" 0}
        @{"PasteTrack" link "PASTETRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETCUERATE" "GETCUERATE <id>"
@next "GETDIR"
@prev "CUTTRACK"

Name
        GETCUERATE <id>

Function
        Returns the samplerate used in the Cuelist file if possible (meaning
        that there must exist an Audio type track).

Synopsis
        <special ID>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID

Results
        Return sample rate used in Cuelist file if possible.

Errors
        If RC=5 then there was no Audio track type in Cuelist file.

Note

Example
        GetCueRate MyId
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Track samplerate: "result

See also
        @{"SetTrack" LINK "SETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETDIR" "GETDIR <title> [path]"
@next "GETENTRY"
@prev "GETCUERATE"

Name
        GETDIR <title> [path]

Function
        Opens an asl requester to allow user to select a directory from the
        requester.

Synopsis
        <string> [<string>]

Inputs
        <title> = name on title (required)
        [path]  = optional init-path telling req. where to start

Results
        Result will contain path string if user selected OK. The path
        will be terminated with slash (/) or column (:).

Errors
        If RC=5 then requester was canceled (or other errors).

Note
        Remember to put double quotes around titles/paths with spaces.

Example
        GetDir '"Choose a sampledir:"' 'Work:Samples'
        if rc=0 then say "You selected: "result

See also
        @{"GetFile" link "GETFILE" 0}
        @{"ListDir" link "LISTDIR" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETENTRY" "GETENTRY <id> <track> <entry> <stem>"
@next "GETENV"
@prev "GETDIR"

Name
        GETENTRY <id> <track> <entry> <stem>

Function
        Get preferences on an entry and puts them in stem. You can use this
        also to copy an entry.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <integer> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        Track   = Track number (1-100)
        Entry   = Entry number to get info on
        Stem    = stem name

Results

        Returns misc data in stem. See {"AddEntry" LINK "SETENTRY" 0} for details.

Errors
        If RC=10 then the track number was <1 or >100.
        If RC=5 then the entry probably didn't exists

Note

Example

        GetEntry MyID 1 1 ENTRY
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say ENTRY.NAME

See also
        @{"SetEntry" link "SETENTRY" 0}
        @{"AddEntry" link "ADDENTRY" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETENV" "GETENV <envname>"
@next "GETFILE"
@prev "GETENTRY"

Name
        GETENV <envname>

Function
        Tries to return global env variable (string). Uses the dos/GetVar()
        function (global+string). You may use SetEnv to set the envelope. You
        can also set it from other programs (eg. "c:SetEnv").

Synopsis
        <string>

Inputs
        <envname>       = string name on env you want returned

Results
        env value (string) in result

Errors
        If RC=5 then the env didn't exist.

Note

Example
        GetEnv "QMASTER"
        if (RC~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "QMaster path: "result

  or

        address command "c:requestfile >env:file"
        GetEnv "file"
        If (rc~=0) then say "file="result


See also
        @{"SetEnv" link "SETENV" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETFILE" "GETFILE <title> [<path> [file]]"
@next "GETPREFS"
@prev "GETENV"

Name
        GETFILE <title> [<path> [file]]

Function
        Opens an asl requester to allow user to select path and a file.

Synopsis
        <string> [<string> [<string>]]

Inputs
        title   = title on requester (required)
        path    = optional path to start from
        file    = optional file (if path) to start with

Results
        Result contain path and file with slash or column initialized.

Errors
        If RC=5 then requester was canceled (or another error)

Note
        Remember to put double quotes around title, path and filename if they
        contain spaces or special chars (:) etc.

Example
        GetFile "'Please choose a cuelist:'" "Studio16_3:Cuelists/" ".Cue"
        if rc=0 then say "You choosed: "result

See also
        @{"GetDir" link "GETDIR" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETPREFS" "GETPREFS <id> <stem>"
@next "GETSTRING"
@prev "GETFILE"

Name
        GETPREFS <id> <stem>

Function
        Returns preferences of a Cuelist file header. Can be used to copy
        Cuelist files or to adjust an already existing one.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        stem    = different settings.
                  See @{"SetPrefs" LINK "SETPREFS" 0} for details.

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then there was probably an error in a stem or ID was invalid.

Note

Example
        GetPrefs MyID PREFS
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Length: "PREFS.TOTALLENGTH/100" seconds"

See also
        @{"SetPrefs" LINK "SETPREFS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETSTRING" "GETSTRING [<title> [bodytext]]"
@next "GETSAMPLEPREFS"
@prev "GETPREFS"

Name
        GETSTRING [<title> [bodytext]]

Function
        Lets user type in a string in an input gadget. Current limit is 300
        chars.

Synopsis
        [<string> [<string>]]

Inputs
        title   = optional title on the requester title
        bodytxt = optional body text in gadget. You cannot use this arg alone.

Results
        RESULT contains string typed if any

Errors
        If RC=5 then the string requester was aborted (or empty string).

Note
        This comand require 'reqtools.library' version 38. The archive is
        available from Aminet in util/libs/

Example
        GetString "'My title'" "'Please type a string:'"
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "You typed: "RESULT

See also

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETSAMPLEPREFS" "GETSAMPLEPREFS <samplefilename> <stem> [<mode>]"
@next "GETTRACK"
@prev "GETSTRING"

Name
        GETSAMPLEPREFS <samplefilename> <stem> [<mode>]

Function
        Returns misc data on a Studio 16 sample file such as samplerate,
        volume, pan etc. Useful with setting crops-in/out and calculate time
        and more. To alter sample prefs use @{"SetSamplePrefs" LINK "SETSAMPLEPREFS" 0}.

Synopsis
        <string> <string> <string>

Inputs
        Samplefilename  = name on samplefile to get prefs from
        stem            = stem to put the data in:
        mode            = if keyword "FULL" (uppercase) is used then the comand
                          will initialize a SampleClip table as well.

        <stem>.SAMPLERATE       = sample rate of file
        <stem>.SIZE             = editsize in number of samples
        <stem>.VOLUME           = volume (not calculated)
        <stem>.PAN              = pan (not calculated)
        <stem>.SMPTE            = SMPTE stamp of file as string
        <stem>.FILTER           = filter setting of file

        From 1.2

        <stem>.REALSIZE         = real size of file in number of samples
        <stem>.MODE             = "FULL" or "", reflects comand option

        If option "FULL" is used:

        <stem>.START.[1-128]    = sample clip start
        <stem>.END.[1-128]      = sample clip end

        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].NAME       = name on region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].START      = start of region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].END        = end of region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].SAMPLERATE = rate of region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].VOLUME     = volume of region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].PAN        = pan of region
        <stem>.REGION.[1-32].SMPTE      = smpte of region

Results
        none

Errors
        if RC=5 then file was probably not found or not a Studio 16 sample file
        (must be of v3 (KWK3)).

Note
        Volume and pan is calculated by dividing on 32. You also subtract 100
        from volume to get real dB value.

        Studio 16 is basing all sample sizes on the 'virtual' editsize so it
        may not corrospond to the real size on the file. This behaviour is
        normal.

        Using option "FULL" takes longer time. Also note that you may leave
        a loop if <stem>.END.x equals null which means end of table.

Example
        GetFile '"Pick a file"' "samples:"
        if rc=5 then exit
                else file=result

        GetSamplePrefs "'"file"'" SAMPLE
        if rc=5 then exit

        say "Samplerate: "SAMPLE.SAMPLERATE
        say "Size:       "SAMPLE.SIZE
        say "Time:       "SAMPLE.SIZE/SAMPLE.SAMPLERATE

See also
        @{"SetSamplePrefs" LINK "SETSAMPLEPREFS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "GETTRACK" "GETTRACK <id> <track> <stem>"
@next "HELP"
@prev "GETSAMPLEPREFS"

Name
        GETTRACK <id> <track> <stem>

Function
        Returns preferences of the <track> in stems if track exists.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track number (1-100) you want prefs for
        stem    = prefix stem name. See @{"SetTrack" LINK "SETTRACK" 0} for details.

Results
        none

Errors
        if RC=10 then track number was invalid <1 or >100
        if RC=5 the track may probably didn't exist

Note

Example
        GetTrack MyID 1 TRACK
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say TRACK.TRACKNAME"="TRACK.TRACKTYPE

See also
        @{"SetTrack" LINK "SETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "HELP" "HELP <>"
@next "INITPROGRESS"
@prev "GETTRACK"

Name
        HELP

Function
        This comand will dump a help page in a console with a comand list and
        its syntax. Should only be used locally during development.

Synopsis
        none

Inputs
        none

Results
        Text page in a console.

Errors
        none

Note

Example
        (from CLI/Shell)

        1> run QMaster
        1> rx "address qmaster;help"

        or create an alias/script for it (f.ex "s/QMHELP")


@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "INITPROGRESS" "INITPROGRESS <total> [title]"
@next "LISTDIR"
@prev "HELP"

Name
        INITPROGRESS <total> [title]

Function
        Initialize a progress bar window and init a special structure with
        total. Useful when your script will do larger operations to show user
        progress in the job.

Synopsis
        <integer> [<string>]

Inputs
        total   = total number to count
        string  = optional title on progress window

Results
        RESULT contains pointer to a special private structure. The pointer is
        put in a resource track which allow you to issue a "ResourceTrack"
        comand to the host to remove it if your script fails and leave it in
        memory (as with OPENCUE).

Errors
        If RC=5 then the window couldn't be opened or the value/title was
        wrong.

Note

Example
        InitProgress 250 "'My Progress'"
        if (rc~=0) then say "Couldn't open Progress window"
                else p=result

See also
        @{"UPDATEPROGRESS" link "UPDATEPROGRESS" 0}
        @{"CLOSEPROGRESS" link "CLOSEPROGRESS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "LISTDIR" "LISTDIR <path/pattern> <stem>"
@next "LOADTRACK"
@prev "INITPROGRESS"

Name
        LISTDIR <path/pattern> <stem>

Function
        Can list the contents of a directory and put the file and directory
        names in a stem.

Synopsis
        <string> <string>

Inputs
        path/pattern = directory to list with pattern
        stem         = stem to put the file/dir names into

Results
        none

        The <stem> will look like:

        <stem>.1 = "X....."

        <stem>.COUNT = total number of files/dirs

        Note that the first char (X) in each name is a TYPE description.
        If "F" then the entry is a FILENAME
        If "D" then the entry is a DIRECTORY

Errors
        If RC=5 then you tried to lock a non-dir, the dir didn't exist, you
        was out of memory or there was a disk error.

Note

Example
        ListDir "Studio16_3:Cuelists/#?.Cue" DIRLST
        if rc~=0 then do
                say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                exit;end

        /* list the content */

        do i=1 to DIRLST.COUNT
          if left(DIRLST.i,1)="D" then say " (DIR) "right(DIRLST.i,length(DIRLST.i)-1)
          if left(DIRLST.i,1)="F" then say "(FILE) "right(DIRLST.i,length(DIRLST.i)-1)
          end

See also
        @{"GetDir" link "GETDIR" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "LOADTRACK" "LOADTRACK <id> <trackfilename>"
@next "NUMBEROFENTRIES"
@prev "LISTDIR"

Name
        LOADTRACK <id> <trackfilename>

Function
        Adds a diskbased track file (TRAX) to the Cuelist file in memory. The
        track file can be generated by Studio 16 or the SaveTrack comand.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <string>

Inputs
        ID              = File ID to add the track to
        trackfilename   = path/filename on trackfile

Results
        Tracknumber this track became (also number of tracks)

Errors
        if RC=5 then the file couldn't be loaded or file wasn't trackfile

Note
        Only one track is currently supported.

Example
        LoadTrack MyID "'Studio16_3:Cuelists/tracks/Special.track'"
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say result

See also
        @{"SaveTrack" LINK "SAVETRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "NUMBEROFENTRIES" "NUMBEROFENTRIES <id> <track>"
@next "NUMBEROFTRACKS"
@prev "LOADTRACK"

Name
        NUMBEROFENTRIES <id> <track>

Function
        Returns number of entries that exist on a <track>.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track (1-100) to count

Results
        Returns number of entries on track 0-5000

Errors
        If RC=10 then <track> number was invalid
        If RC=5 then track probably didn't exist

Note

Example
        NumberOfEntries MyID 1
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "There are "result" entries on track 1"

See also
        @{"NumberOfTracks" LINK "NUMBEROFTRACKS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "NUMBEROFTRACKS" "NUMBEROFTRACKS <id>"
@next "OPENCUE"
@prev "NUMBEROFENTRIES"

Name
        NUMBEROFTRACKS <id>

Function
        Return number of tracks contained in a Cuelist file.

Synopsis
        <special ID>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID

Results
        Number of tracks 0-100 where 0 is no tracks

Errors
        If RC=5 then the ID was invalid

Note

Example
        NumberOfTracks MyID
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Tracks: "result

See also
        @{"AddTrack" LINK "ADDTRACK" 0}
        @{"SetTrack" LINK "SETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "OPENCUE" "OPENCUE <cuelistfilename>"
@next "PASTETRACK"
@prev "NUMBEROFTRACKS"

Name
        OPENCUE <cuelistfilename>

Function
        This is the "heart" comand in QMaster. This comand will load and
        process a Studio 16 Cuelist file into memory. The comand will parse the
        comand and create special structures to make changes appear extremely
        fast.

        This comand is necessary to use to be able to do anything with a
        Cuelist file. You may have upto 256 Cuelist files opened at once
        (restricted by RT). Do not alter the result.

        When you have made your changes use the UpdateCue to update them to
        disk. Always make sure to use the CloseCue to release the
        resources used by this comand.

Synopsis
        <string>

Inputs
        cuelistfilename = path/name on Cuelist file (TLC1) to load

Results
        A special ID to be used with other comands.

Errors
        If RC=5 then you the file didn't exist or the file wasn't a Cuelist
        file or you was out of memory

Note
        You can not load track files with this comand. Use the LoadTrack comand
        to add a trackfile to an already existing cuelist file in memory.

Example
        OpenCuelist "'Studio16_3:Cuelists/Cool.Cue'"
        if (rc~=0) then do
                say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                exit 5
                end

See also
        @{"CloseCue" LINK "CLOSECUE" 0}
        @{"UpdateCue" LINK "UPDATECUE" 0}
        @{"LoadTrack" LINK "LOADTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "PASTETRACK" "PASTETRACK <id>"
@next "QUIT"
@prev "OPENCUE"

Name
        PASTETRACK <id>

Function
        Will paste a track already copied by CopyTrack to the cuelist file ID.
        If no track was copied the comand will return without doing anything.

Synopsis
        <special ID>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID to add the copied track to

Results
        Track number the paste resulted in. Also number of tracks.

Errors
        If RC=5 then there was no track to paste or track table in destination
        was full or memory was full.

Note

Example
        PasteTrack MyID
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Became track: "result

See also
        @{"CopyTrack" LINK "COPYTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "QUIT" "QUIT"
@next "REG"
@prev "PASTETRACK"

Name
        QUIT

Function
        Will quit QMaster. It activates the Resource Track Environment and
        cleans up any resources allocated with OpenCue and InitProgress.

Synopsis
        <>
Inputs
        <>

Results
        <>

Errors
        <>

Note
        Be careful!

Example
        QUIT

See also

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "REG" "REG"
@next "REMENTRY"
@prev "QUIT"

Name
        REG

Function
        Returns registry data in a string. Can be used to welcome a user.

Synopsis
        <>

Inputs
        <>

Results
        A string containing user data or status of registry (DEMOVERSION etc.)

Errors
        <>

Note

Example
   REG
   if result~="DEMOVERSION" then say "Welcome "right(result,length(result)-13)

See also
        @{"VERSION" LINK "VERSION" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "REMENTRY" "REMENTRY <id> <track> <entry>"
@next "REMTRACK"
@prev "REG"

Name
        REMENTRY <id> <track> <entry>

Function
        Will try to remove an entry from a track. The resources for the entry
        is released.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <integer>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track (1-100) to remove entry from
        entry   = entry (1-5000) to remove

Results
        Returns number of entries left on the track

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number of entry number was out of range
        If RC=5 then the entry didn't exist.

Note
        The entry will be lost forever from memory so if you need if make sure
        you copy its setting first (GetEntry).

Example
        RemEntry MyID 2 10
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Entries left: "result

See also
        @{"GetEntry" LINK "GETENTRY" 0}
        @{"AddEntry" LINK "ADDENTRY" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "REMTRACK" "REMTRACK <id> <track>"
@next "REQUEST"
@prev "REMENTRY"

Name
        REMTRACK <id> <track>

Function
        Removes a whole track and all entries. Releases resources as well.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track number (1-100) to remove

Results
        Number of tracks left

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number was out of range
        If RC=5 then the track didn't exist

Note
        When the comand was successful the track is lost forever from memory.
        Use the CopyTrack function to preserve the track.

Example
        RemTrack MyID 3
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say "Tracks left: "result

See also
        @{"CopyTrack" LINK "COPYTRACK" 0}
        @{"AddTrack" LINK "ADDTRACK" 0}
        @{"GetTrack" LINK "GETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "REQUEST" "REQUEST <title> <body> <buttons>"
@next "RESOURCETRACK"
@prev "REMTRACK"

Name
        REQUEST <title> <body> <buttons>

Function
        Opens an easy request to allow user select one or more options. You can
        put a title on the request, extensive text and format your buttons as
        you like.

Synopsis
        <string> <string> <string>

Inputs
        title   = name on the requester
        body    = body text. May contain linefeeds and/or "\n"
        buttons = button format string f.ex. "OK" or "OK|CANCEL"

Results
        Result contain a number representing button pressed. The rightmost is
        always 0 and then you start counting from left as 1. F.ex, the buttons
        "Quit|About|OK" will give number 1,2,0.

Errors
        If RC=5 then you was out of memory.

Note

Example
        Request "'Test request'" LF"'This is a test'"LF"'... hey!'" "OK"
        Request "'Test request'" "'\nThis is a test\n... hey!'" "OK"

See also

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "RESOURCETRACK" "RESOURCETRACK <>"
@next "SAVETRACK"
@prev "REQUEST"

Name
        RESOURCETRACK <>

Function
        Invokes QMaster's internal Resource Tracking function. QMaster will
        check if there are resources left for OpenCue and InitProgress and
        remove them if there are any. This comand should only be used for
        debug reasons and never implemented in a public script.

        QMaster's RT will also be activated when QMaster exit.

Synopsis
        <>

Inputs
        <>

Results
        <>

Errors
        <>

Note
        Never issue a RT while a script is executing.

Example
        rx "address qmaster;resourcetrack"

        or use the shell script "s/QMRT"

See also
        @{"OpenCue" link "OPENCUE" 0}
        @{"InitProgress" link "INITPROGRESS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SAVETRACK" "SAVETRACK <id> <track> <trackfilename>"
@next "SECONDSTOSMPTE"
@prev "RESOURCETRACK"

Name
        SAVETRACK <id> <track> <trackfilename>

Function
        Saves a track in memory to a TRAX file (track file). It is equal with
        the ones Studio 16 creates and can therefor be loaded directly into
        Studio 16 or used with the LoadTrack comand.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <string>

Inputs
        ID              = File ID
        track           = track number (1-100) to save to disk
        trackfilename   = path/name to give the track file

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then the file couldn't be opened or an write error occured
        (eg. disk full)

Note
        The comand only saves one track.

Example
        SaveTrack MyID 4 "'ram:CueTrackBuffer'"
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
              else say "You now may use the paste-track function in Studio 16"

See also
        @{"LoadTrack" LINK "LOADTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SECONDSTOSMPTE" "SECONDSTOSMPTE [vsystem] <seconds>"
@next "SETENTRY"
@prev "SAVETRACK"

Name
        SECONDSTOSMPTE [vsystem] <seconds>

Function
        Converts seconds into a SMPTE stamp based on video system (PAL/NTSC).

Synopsis
        [<string>] <float>

Inputs
        string  = this is optional. If used it must be either PAL or NTSC in
                  uppercase. If not used the program will try to auto detect
                  which system is in use.
        float   = seconds to convert. May be float.

Results
        A SMPTE stamp in sting format "HH:MM:SS:FF"

Errors
        If RC=5 then seconds was an invalid number

Note
        Due to SMPTE stamps resolution you may notice a small error when
        converting the smpte stamp back to seconds.

Example
        SecondsToSMPTE "PAL" 233.1201
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
              else say result

See also
        @{"SMPTEToSeconds" LINK "SMPTETOSECONDS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SETENTRY" "SETENTRY <id> <track> <entry> <stem>"
@next "SETENV"
@prev "SECONDSTOSMPTE"

Name
        SETENTRY <id> <track> <entry> <stem>

Function
        Modifies an already existing entry on a track.  See note.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <integer> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track number (1-100)
        entry   = entry number (1-5000) to change
        stem    = holds the new settings.
                  See @{"AddEntry" LINK "ADDENTRY" 0} for details

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number or entry number was out of range
        If RC=5 then track or entry didn't exist

Note
        If you only need to alter a few settings then make sure to use the
        GetEntry first or else the values not defined from SetEntry will be
        turned into default values.

        You are not allowed to change entry type.

Example

        GetEntry MyID 2 10 ENTRY
        if (rc~=0) then call quitscript

        ENTRY.NAME="New name"

        SetEntry MyID 2 10 ENTRY
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
              else say result


See also
        @{"AddEntry" LINK "ADDENTRY" 0}
        @{"GetEntry" LINK "GETENTRY" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SETENV" "SETENV <envname> <envstring>"
@next "SETPREFS"
@prev "SETENTRY"

Name
        SETENV <envname> <envstring>

Function
        Sets a global env (in ENV:) accessible to any program. The comand uses
        the dos/SetVar() function to set the env.

Synopsis
        <string> <string>

Inputs
        envname         = name on the global env
        envstring       = ascii string to store in envname

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then the env couldn't be set.

Note

Example
        SetEnv "TERM" "Amiga"
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

See also
        @{"GetEnv" LINK "GETENV" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SETPREFS" "SETPREFS <id> <stem>"
@next "SETSAMPLEPREFS"
@prev "SETENV"

Name
        SETPREFS <id> <stem>

Function
        Sets new preferences to a cuelist file header. Here you can alter
        length, time options, bpm, flag positions and so on.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        stem    = different settings

        <stem>.WINLEFT          window left position when zipped. Def=0
        <stem>.WINTOP           window top position when zipped. Def=10
        <stem>.WINWIDTH         window width when zipped. Def=640
        <stem>.WINHEIGHT        window height when zipped. Def=256
        <stem>.CUELISTPATH      path to Cuelists. Must be ended with : or /
                                Def="Studio16_3:Cuelists/"
        <stem>.TRACKPATH        path to tracks. Must be ended with : or /
                                Def="Studio16_3:Cuelists/Tracks/"
        <stem>.CUELISTNAME      name on this cuelist. Same as your save name
                                Def="Untitled.Cue"
        <stem>.TRACKNAME        name on tracks you save.
                                Def="Track.Cue"
        <stem>.FADEINTYPE       see studio16file.i|h include for details
        <stem>.FADEOUTTYPE      see studio16file.i|h include for details
        <stem>.MAXTIME          max fade time. Def=1.0000 second
        <stem>.GRIDSPACING      time between each grid. Def=1.0000 second
        <stem>.STARTTIME        start time of this cuelist. Def=0.0000
        <stem>.TOTALLENGTH      length*100 in seconds. Def=30000 (300 seconds)
        <stem>.VIEWSIZE         size of visable portion (zoom). sec*100
        <stem>.VIEWSTART        start of visable portion. sec*100
        <stem>.BPM              beats per minuttes. Def=120
        <stem>.BPMX             signature X/Y. Def=4
        <stem>.BPMY             signature X/Y. Def=4
        <stem>.TIMEOPTION       see studio16file.i|h include for details
        <stem>.F1FLAG           F1-F10 flag position in sec. Def=-1.0000 (off)
        <stem>.F2FLAG
        <stem>.F3FLAG
        <stem>.F4FLAG
        <stem>.F5FLAG
        <stem>.F6FLAG
        <stem>.F7FLAG
        <stem>.F8FLAG
        <stem>.F9FLAG
        <stem>.F10FLAG
        <stem>.F1COMMENT        string comment to flag F1-F10. Def=none
        <stem>.F2COMMENT
        <stem>.F3COMMENT
        <stem>.F4COMMENT
        <stem>.F5COMMENT
        <stem>.F6COMMENT
        <stem>.F7COMMENT
        <stem>.F8COMMENT
        <stem>.F9COMMENT
        <stem>.F10COMMENT
        <stem>.STARTFLAG        startflag position. Def=10.0000
        <stem>.LOCATEFLAG       locateflag position. Def=10.0000
        <stem>.PUNCHINFLAG      punchin flag postition. Def=0.0000
        <stem>.PUNCHOUTFLAG     punchout flag position. Def=0.0000 (off)
        <stem>.STARTCOMMENT     string comment to start flag. Def=none
        <stem>.LOCATECOMMENT    string comment to locate flag. Def=none
        <stem>.PUNCHINCOMMENT   string comment to punchin flag. Def=none
        <stem>.PUNCHOUTCOMMENT  string comment to punchout flag. Def=none

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then the stems probably contained an error or ID was invalid.

Note

Example
        GetPrefs MyID PREFS
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

        PREFS.CUELISTNAME="Test.Cue"
        PREFS.TOTALLENGTH=5*60*100  /* 5 minuttes */

        SetPrefs MyID PREFS
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR


See also
        @{"GetPrefs" LINK "GETPREFS" 0}
        @{"CreateCue" LINK "CREATECUE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SETSAMPLEPREFS" "SETSAMPLEPREFS <samplefilename> <stem> [<mode>]"
@next "SETTRACK"
@prev "SETPREFS"

Name
        SETSAMPLEPREFS <samplefilename> <stem> [<mode>]

Function
        Alters misc data on a Studio 16 sample file such as samplerate,
        volume, pan etc. Useful with setting crops-in/out and calculate time
        and more. To read sampleprefs use @{"GetSamplePrefs" LINK "GETSAMPLEPREFS" 0}.

Synopsis
        <string> <string> <string>

Inputs
        Samplefilename  = name on samplefile to get prefs from
        stem            = stem to put the data in:
        mode            = if keyword "FULL" (uppercase) is used then the comand
                          will initialize a SampleClip table as well.

        To see list of stem variables @{"GetSamplePrefs" LINK "GETSAMPLEPREFS" 0}.

Results
        none

Errors
        if RC=5 then file was probably not found or not a Studio 16 sample file
        (must be of v3 (KWK3)).

WARNING
        Be careful with tempering with the EDITSIZE, REALSIZE, SampleClip and
        Region values. Do not touch if you don't know what you're doing! If
        the values are invalid Studio 16 may refuse to read the sample. For
        more information on SampleClips and Regions please download the
        Studio16add.lha archive from Aminet.

Note
        Volume and pan is calculated by dividing on 32. You also subtract 100
        from volume to get real dB value.

        Studio 16 is basing all sample sizes on the 'virtual' editsize so it
        may not corrospond to the real size on the file. This behaviour is
        normal.

        Using option "FULL" takes longer time. Also note that you may leave
        a loop if <stem>.END.x equals null which means end of table.

Example
        GetFile '"Pick a file"' "samples:"
        if rc=5 then exit
                else file=result

        GetSamplePrefs "'"file"'" SAMPLE
        if rc=5 then exit

        SAMPLE.SAMPLERATE=48000

        SetSamplePrefs "'"file"'" SAMPLE
        if rc=5 then exit

See also
        @{"GetSamplePrefs" LINK "GETSAMPLEPREFS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode


@node "SETTRACK" "SETTRACK <id> <track> <stem>"
@next "SMPTETOSECONDS"
@prev "SETSAMPLEPREFS"

Name
        SETTRACK <id> <track> <stem>

Function
        Sets misc preferences on an already existing track.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <string>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track number (1-100) to change
        stem    = stem holding different settings
                  See @{"AddTrack" LINK "ADDTRACK" 0} for more details.

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number was out of range
        If RC=5 then the track may not exist or there is an error in a stem

Note
        You should use the GetTrack comand if you are only gonna make a few
        changes since else the other variables will be set to default values.

        You are not allowed to change track type.

Example
        GetTrack MyID 2 TRACK

        If TRACK.TRACKTYPE="AREXX" then do
                TRACK.TRACKNAME="RX Chan"
                TRACK.PORTNAME="REXX"
                end

        SetTrack MyID 2 TRACK
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

See also
        @{"AddTrack" LINK "ADDTRACK" 0}
        @{"GetTrack" LINK "GETTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SMPTETOSECONDS" "SMPTETOSECONDS [vsystem] <smptestamp>"
@next "SWAPTRACKS"
@prev "SETTRACK"

Name
        SMPTETOSECONDS [vsystem] <smptestamp>

Function
        Converts a SMPTE stamp into seconds based on video system PAL or NTSC.

Synopsis
        [<string>] <string>

Inputs
        vsystem = this is optional. If used it must be either PAL or NTSC in
                  uppercase. If not used the program will try to auto detect
                  which system is in use.
        smpte   = a string holding a SMPTE stamp in format "HH:MM:SS:FF"

Results
        Number of seconds (float)

Errors
        If RC=5 then the SMPTE stamp was invalid

Note
        Be aware of SMPTE stamp's resolutions when converting back and forth.

Example
        VIDEO
        system=result

        SMPTEToSeconds system "00:12:03:23"
        If (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else say system": "result

    PAL to NTSC:

        SMPTEToSeconds PAL "00:12:03:23"
        SecondsToSMPTE NTSC result

See also
        @{"SecondsToSMPTE" LINK "SECONDSTOSMPTE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "SWAPTRACKS" "SWAPTRACKS <id> <track1> <track2>"
@next "TRACKTYPE"
@prev "SMPTETOSECONDS"

Name
        SWAPTRACKS <id> <track1> <track2>

Function
        Swaps two tracks in a Cuelistfile.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer> <integer>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track1  = track 1 (1-100) you want to swap with:
        track2  = track 2 (1-100) you want to swap with track 1

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=10 then one of the track numbers was out of range
        If RC=5 then track didn't exist or ID was invalid or track1=track2

Note

Example

See also

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "TRACKTYPE" "TRACKTYPE <id> <track>"
@next "UPDATECUE"
@prev "SWAPTRACKS"

Name
        TRACKTYPE <id> <track>

Function
        Returns the track type string of a track if it exists.

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        ID      = File ID
        track   = track number (1-100)

Results
        Returns "AUDIO" or "AREXX"

Errors
        If RC=10 then track number was out of range
        If RC=5 then track didn't exist or ID was invalid

Note

Example
        TrackType MyID 2
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR
                else "Track is of type "result

See also
        @{"AddTrack" LINK "ADDTRACK" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "UPDATECUE" "UPDATECUE <id> [newcuelistfile]"
@next "UPDATEPROGRESS"
@prev "TRACKTYPE"

Name
        UPDATECUE <id> [newcuelistfile]

Function
        Updates a Cuelist file in memory loaded with OpenCue. All changes
        that you have made will be saved back to the same file or optionally to
        a new file.

        When saving back you could provide an option like "SAVE or SAVE AS".
        The latter could pop up a filerequester and if defined the path/file
        could be given as the optional arg.

Synopsis
        <special ID> [<string>]

Inputs
        ID         = File ID to update
        newcuelist = this argument is optional. If it's used the updated
                     information will be saved to this file instead.

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then the newfile couldn't be opened, or a write error occured
        (eg. disk full).

Note
        Be careful with saving back to same file as any failure may destroy the
        file.

Example
        UpdateCue MyID "ram:NewCue.Cue"
        if (rc~=0) then say QMASTER.LASTERROR

See also
        @{"CloseCue" LINK "CLOSECUE" 0}
        @{"OpenCue" LINK "OPENCUE" 0}
        @{"CreateCue" LINK "CREATECUE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "UPDATEPROGRESS" "UPDATEPROGRESS <progress> <current>"
@next "VERSION"
@prev "UPDATECUE"

Name
        UPDATEPROGRESS <progress> <current>

Function
        Updates a progressbar previously opened with INITPROGRESS. The bar
        graph is only updated increasingly. You can press the window's
        closegadget to abort the progress bar. The comand will then return 5
        in RC and the script should act on it. The progress bar has a
        resolution of 300 pixels (internally 1/1000).

Synopsis
        <special ID> <integer>

Inputs
        progress = pointer to progress bar structure
        current  = current value. If higher than total it will be truncated.

Results
        none

Errors
        If RC=5 then user aborted the progress bar

Note
        Only updates increasingly

Example
        InitProgress 300 "'My progress'"
        p=result

        do i=1 to 300
                UpdateProgress p i
                if (rc~=0) then do
                        say "Aborted..."
                        CloseProgress p
                        exit
                        end
                end

See also
        @{"INITPROGRESS" link "INITPROGRESS" 0}
        @{"CLOSEPROGRESS" link "CLOSEPROGRESS" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "VERSION" "VERSION"
@next "VIDEO"
@prev "UPDATEPROGRESS"

Name
        VERSION

Function
        This comand will return a string containing the QMaster version.

Synopsis
        <>

Inputs
        <>

Results
        A string containing version string. Remember to use the
        OPTIONS RESULTS.

Errors
        <>

Note
        <>

Example
        VERSION
        say "You are using "result

        Or the dos script "s/QMVERSION"

See also
        @{"REG" LINK "REG" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "VIDEO" "VIDEO <>"
@next "TROUBLESHOOTING"
@prev "VERSION"

Name
        VIDEO

Function
        This function tries to resolve which video system the machine is using.
        It will return either PAL or NTSC if ok, or an error.

Synopsis
        <>

Inputs
        <>

Results
        A string containing video system (PAL or NTSC).

Errors
        If RC=5 then the comand wasn't capable or determine which video
        system this machine use. This can be a problem in future..

Note

Example
        VIDEO
        say "Video system: "result

See also
        @{"Cards" link "CARDS" 0}
        @{"SMPTEToSeconds" link "SMPTETOSECONDS" 0}
        @{"SecondsToSMPTE" link "SECONDSTOSMPTE" 0}

@{"COMAND LIST" link "AREXX" 0}
@endnode

@node "TROUBLESHOOTING" "Trouble-shooting"
@next "FAQ"
@prev "VIDEO"

@{b}TROUBLESHOOTING@{ub}


        @{b}ERRORS THAT CAN BE RETURNED BY QMASTER.LASTERROR@{ub}


        All error levels (5,10 and 20) sets QMASTER.LASTERROR. RC(0) clears it.


        COULDN'T AUTODETECT VIDEO SYSTEM!

                This error will occure if QMaster was unable to resolve the
                video system it is used on. This could be due to a future
                update of the execbase or hardware in the Amiga. Please report
                this error along with your computer system data.

        COULDN'T MATCHFIRST() - CHECK PATTERN!

                An error occured with ListDir. Probably a wrong pattern
                argument or a wrong path or an error on the HD.

        ENTRY DOESN'T EXIST!

                This means that the specified entry number didn't exist on this
                track.

        ENTRY OVERLAP!

                The entry ADDENTRY was trying to add would have overlapped an
                already existing one.

        ERROR ALLOCATING ASL REQUESTER!

                You where probably out of memory or used illegal chars in
                strings etc.

        ERROR ALLOCATING EASY REQUEST!

                You where probably out of memory or used illegal chars in
                strings or the button format string was wrong.

        ERROR GETTING ENV!

                Something went wrong trying to get an env variable with the
                dos/GetVar() function.

        ERROR IN NUMBER!

                An arg given to a comand contained alpha chars when a number
                was expected. You should debug your program or create a check
                routine to avoid this error.

        ERROR OPENING FILE FOR READ!
        ERROR OPENING FILE FOR WRITE!
        ERROR OPENING FILE FOR READ/WRITE!

                The comand couldn't open a requested file. It can be many
                reasons for this. Like your disk is full or is invalidated, the
                file you try to open is maybe locked or the file simply doesn't
                exists (read).

        ERROR OPENING OUTPUT CONSOLE!

                The resource tracking facillity couldn't open its window. You
                could be out of memory or the CON: device handler is not
                available of some reason.

        ERROR OPENING WINDOW!

                Couldn't open the progress barwindow. You are probably out of
                memory or the the window couldn't fit on the current
                screenmode. The window tries to open on default public screen.

        ERROR READING FILE!

                An error occured while reading a file. It can be that the file
                is mangled or destroyed. 

        ERROR SETTING ENV!

                An error occured while trying to set an env variable using the
                dos/SetVar() function.

        ERROR SETTING STEM!

                A comand failed to set a stem value. It could be due to a
                missing stem or a alpha in a stem that should be integer.

        ERROR WRITING FILE!

                An error occured while writing to a file. Most likely your disk
                went out of space (disk full) or your disk could have a
                validate error or the file could be destroyed.

        INVALID ENTRY NUMBER!

                An entry number was out of range <1 or >5000. You should
                provide a safty routine to avoid this error.

        INVALID ID!

                The ID used is invalid (not a Cuefile structure). This will
                occure if you don't act on errors from the OpenCue or CreateCue
                comands.

        INVALID SMPTE!

                The SMPTE stamp was illegal. A SMPTE stamp must be in the
                following format: "HH:MM:SS:FF" where HH=Hours, MM=Minuttes,
                SS=Seconds and FF=Frames. Frames can be between 0-24 on a PAL
                system while on a NTSC system it can be between 0-29.

        INVALID TIME!

                The time the comand got contained alpha chars or was too big.

        INVALID TRACK NUMBER!

                The track number given to the comand was out of range <1 or
                >100. You should provide a safty routine to avoid this error.

        INVALID TRACK TYPE!

                The track type was illegal. Only two track types are supported:
                "AUDIO" and "AREXX" which both must be given in UPPER case.

        NO STRING!

                The comand misses a string, probably in a stem.

        NO TRACK IN BUFFER!

                Using PasteTrack you may get this error if no track was copied
                using the CopyTrack.

        OUT OF MEMORY!

                Severe error. You are out of memory. At this error you should
                terminate the script after a proper clean up. Try to close
                windows/programs and restart script. If still error you could
                try to reboot the machine or release resources.

        PROGRESS ABORT!

                User closed (aborted) the progress window.

        REQUESTER CANCEL!

                User canceled a Asl requester.

        SAME TRACK USED!

                Error from SwapTracks. If track1 and track2 are equal you will
                get this error.

        SEVERE ERROR - NO FILE HANDLER!

                This error should never occure. That means the internal
                filehandler pointer for the ID si missing. Please report to
                author if you ever experience this error. Supply script and
                cuefile it occured with.

        STRING REQUEST ABORT!

                The string requester was empty or user aborted it.

        SYNTAX ERROR!

                The arguments that was given to the comand was wrong. You
                probably forgot an arg or gave one too much. Never publish a
                script that returns this error.

        TRACK DOESN'T EXIST!

                The track number the comand got didn't exist.

        TRACK TABLE IS FULL!

                The limit on 100 tracks was reached. Studio 16 can't handle
                more that 100 tracks. Try to remove empty tracks.

        WRONG FILE ID (KWK3)!

                The file the comand opened was not of the needed kind. In this
                case the program needed a Studio 16 sample file (KWK3).

        WRONG FILE ID (TLC1)!

                The file the comand opened was not of the needed kind. In this
                case the program needed a Studio 16 Cuelist file (TLC1).


        @{b}SYSTEM@{ub}

        - The 'LoadQM' comand doesn't start QMaster.

        Make sure that the environmental variable 'QMASTER' is set. Use
        'c:GetEnv "QMASTER"' to check. This should return the path to where
        QMaster is installed. If not see @{"Installation" link "INSTALL" 0}.

        - Arexx scripts fails at the line where 'LoadQM' is.

        Make sure that 'LoadQM' is installed in a directory which is in the
        (global) comand search path (defined with the comand 'path' in
        s:startup-sequence or s:user-startup). To be sure put 'LoadQM' in C:
        (sys:c/).

        - The arexx scripts fails when I want to use the 'GetString' comand.

        Make sure the 'reqtools.library' is installed in LIBS:. The archive can
        be downloaded from Aminet in util/libs/


        @{b}CUELISTS@{ub}

        - When I use the AddTrack/AddEntry comand the file isn't updated when I
          close it.

        Use the @{"UpdateCue" link "UPDATECUE" 0} comand to update changes to current file or to save
        them to another file.


